November\n2020\n.\nFurther reading\nPais, Abraham\n(1983).\nSubtle Is the Lord: The Science and the Life of Albert Einstein\n(Third ed.). Oxford University Press.\nISBN\n978-0-19-520438-4\n.\nOCLC\n8195995\n.\nExternal links\nWikimedia Commons has media related to\nNobel Prize\n.\nListen to this article\n(\n30\nminutes\n)\nThis audio file\nwas created from a revision of this article dated 2 November 2016\n(\n2016-11-02\n)\n, and does not reflect subsequent edits.\n(\nAudio help\n·\nMore spoken articles\n)\nOfficial website\nNobel Prizes by universities and institutes\nv\nt\ne\nNobel Prizes\nLists of Nobel laureates\nNobel Prize medal\nPrizes\nChemistry\nEconomics\n1\nLiterature\nPeace\nPhysics\nPhysiology or Medicine\nLaureates\nby occupation\nHeads of state and government\nby year\nby subject\nChemistry\nEconomics\n1\nLiterature\nPeace\nPhysics\nPhysiology or Medicine\nby\npopulation\ngroup\nBengali\nBlack\nChristian\nFemale\nJewish\nLatin American\nNon-religious\nby continent\nand\nnationality\nAfrican\nEgyptian\nSouth African\nAsian\nArmenian\nChinese\nFilipino\nIndian\nIsraeli\nJapanese\nKorean\nPakistani\nTurkish\nVietnamese\nEuropean\nBelgian\nDanish\nGerman\nGreek\nHungarian\nIrish\nItalian\nPolish\nRomanian\nRussian\nSpanish\nSwedish\nSwiss\nWelsh\nOceanian\nAustralian\nNorth American\nAmerican\nMexican\nSouth American\nArgentine\nBrazilian\nVenezuelan\nby university\nCity University of New York\nColumbia University\nETH Zurich\nHarvard University\nPrinceton University\nWashington University in St. Louis\nNominees\nCatholic priests and religious\nHeads of state and government\nCouples\nWomen\nby subject\nChemistry\n1901–1999\nEconomics\n1\n1901–1999\nLiterature\n1901–1999\n2000–present\nPeace\nIndividuals\n1900–1999\n2000–present\nOrganizations\nPhysics\n1901–1999\nPhysiology or Medicine\n1901–1999\nby groups\nPeace\nAFSC Nobel nominees\nPRIO Director's Shortlist\nby\nClarivate\nFemale\nChemistry\nEconomics\n1\nPhysics\nPhysiology or Medicine\nOrganisations\nNobel Foundation\nNobel Committees\nChemistry\nEconomics\n1\nLiterature\nPhysics\nPhysiology or Medicine\nNorwegian Nobel Committee\nNobel Assembly at the Karolinska Institute\nRelated\nControversies\nLiterature\nPhysics\nPeace\nAlfred Nobel\nBjörkborn Manor\nNobel Banquet\nNobel Laboratory\nLindau Nobel Laureate Meetings\nNobel Monument\nWorld Summit of Nobel Peace Laureates\nPrizes known as the \"Nobel\" of their fields\n1\nNobel Memorial Prize (not one of the original Nobel Prizes).\nv\nt\ne\n2025\nNobel Prize\nlaureates\nChemistry\nSusumu Kitagawa\n(Japan)\nRichard Robson\n(Australia, United Kingdom)\nOmar M. Yaghi\n(Palestine, Jordan, United States)\nLiterature\n(\n2025\n)\nLászló Krasznahorkai\n(Hungary)\nPeace\n(\n2025\n)\nMaría Corina Machado\n(Venezuela)\nPhysics\nJohn Clarke\n(United Kingdom)\nMichel H. Devoret\n(France)\nJohn M. Martinis\n(United States)\nPhysiology or Medicine\nMary E. Brunkow\n(United States)\nFred Ramsdell\n(United States)\nShimon Sakaguchi\n(Japan)\nEconomic Sciences\nJoel Mokyr\n(Netherlands, Israel, United States)\nPhilippe Aghion\n(France)\nPeter Howitt\n(Canada)\nNobel Prize recipients\n2020\n2021\n2022\n2023\n2024\n2025\n2026\nAuthority control databases\nInternational\nGND\nNational\nUnited States\nJapan\nCzech Republic\nIsrael\nOther\nNARA\nYale LUX\nRetrieved from \"\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Nobel_Prize&oldid=1337669928\n\"\nCategories\n:\nNobel Prize\n1895 establishments in Sweden\nAlfred Nobel\nAwards established in 1895\nInternational academic awards\nInternational science and technology awards\nRoyal Swedish Academy of Sciences\nScience and technology in Sweden\nSwedish Culture Canon\nSwedish science and technology awards\nHidden categories:\nArticles containing Swedish-language text\nPages with Swedish IPA\nArticles containing Norwegian-language text\nPages with Norwegian IPA\nWikipedia articles needing clarification from October 2020\nWebarchive template wayback links\nCS1 Norwegian-language sources (no)\nCS1 German-language sources (de)\nCS1 Swedish-language sources (sv)\nCS1 maint: deprecated archival service\nWikipedia articles incorporating a citation from the ODNB\nPages using cite ODNB with id parameter\nArticles with short description\nShort description is different from Wikidata\nWikipedia pages semi-protected against vandalism\nUse dmy dates from March 2022\nArticles containing potentially dated statements from 2024\nAll articles containing potentially dated statements\nAll articles with unsourced statements\nArticles with unsourced statements from December 2024\nArticles needing more viewpoints from May 2024\nArticles containing potentially dated statements from 2016\nFree-content attribution\nFree content from UNESCO\nCommons category link from Wikidata\nArticles with hAudio microformats\nSpoken articles\nArticles containing video clips\nSearch\nSearch\nNobel Prize\n195 languages\nAdd topic","chroma:document":"[\n96\n]\nAll medals made before 1980 were struck in 23\ncarat\ngold. Since then, they have been struck in 18 carat\ngreen gold\nplated with 24 carat gold. The weight of each medal varies with the value of gold, but averages about 175 grams (0.386 lb) for each medal. The diameter is 66 millimetres (2.6 in) and the thickness varies between 5.2 millimetres (0.20 in) and 2.4 millimetres (0.094 in).\n[\n97\n]\nBecause of the high value of their gold content and tendency to be on public display, Nobel medals are subject to medal theft.\n[\n98\n]\n[\n99\n]\n[\n100\n]\nDuring World War II, the medals of German scientists\nMax von Laue\nand\nJames Franck\nwere sent to Copenhagen for safekeeping. When Germany invaded Denmark, Hungarian chemist (and Nobel laureate himself)\nGeorge de Hevesy\ndissolved them in\naqua regia\n(nitro-hydrochloric acid), to prevent confiscation by\nNazi Germany\nand to prevent legal problems for the holders. After the war, the gold was recovered from solution, and the medals re-cast.\n[\n101\n]","title":"Nobel Prize - Wikipedia","headers":"H2: ContentsH1: Nobel PrizeH2: HistoryH3: Nobel FoundationH4: Formation of Nobel FoundationH4: Foundation capital and costH3: Inaugural Nobel prizesH3: Second World WarH3: Prize in Economic SciencesH2: Award processH3: NominationsH3: SelectionH3: Posthumous nominationsH3: Recognition time lagH2: Award ceremonies and related eventsH3: Nobel BanquetH3: Nobel lectureH3: Nobel MindsH2: PrizesH3: MedalsH3: DiplomasH3: Award moneyH2: StatisticsH2: Specially distinguished laureatesH3: Multiple laureatesH3: Family laureatesH2: Reception and controversiesH3: Controversial recipientsH3: Overlooked achievementsH3: Emphasis on discoveries over inventionsH3: GenderH3: Status of the Economic Sciences PrizeH2: Refusals and constraintsH2: ImpactH3: CulturalH2: See alsoH2: NotesH2: ReferencesH3: SourcesH4: BooksH2: Further readingH2: External links"}␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀